Introduction

This document describes the acceptance criteria for the Software Engineering course project by Software House One. The goal of the project, “BrowserMonkey” is to develop a new application browser for documents written in Hypertext Mark-up Language (HTML).

 

The browser is intended for use in agricultural machinery, for example a tractor dashboard, to display documents such as the machinery user manual. It will read and display a document written in HTML, including extensions added by Netscape, although not all HTML and Netscape extensions functionality will be implemented. The acceptance criteria in this document are based on the customer requirements described in the Requirements Specification1.

 

Tests are numbered according to their corresponding requirement and section number in the Requirements Specification1, for example:

 

 

ACC-4-11-0002

 

 

The HTML files containing the test data for the acceptance criteria will be stored in

“se-proj1/SVNRepository/QA Team/baselined/testdata”, and the html for each test is also included in this document. To allow for the possibility of using scripts to extract tests and test results, each test sequence is immediately preceded by the line:

 

<p>********** Test Number: ACC4-11-0001 **********</p>

 

where ACC4-11-0001 corresponds to the requirement, section and test number.

 

The end of all test sequences in the file is followed by the line:

 

<p>********** End of Test Data **********</p>

1        Requirement 1 – Basic Renderer

A basic text renderer, including a simple parser with internet files capability, renderer and Graphical User Interface (GUI).

1.1    Overview

A detailed description of the document character set and HTML character entities supported by BrowserMonkey can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

Test that every supported, displayable ASCII character is rendered correctly.

Preconditions:

None, other than must be able to start BrowserMonkey to open the test data file

1.2    Whitespace

A detailed description of how BrowserMonkey handles whitespace can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

 

Test Number:

ACC1-2-0001

Data file/s:

acc1-2.html

Description:

Test that multiple spaces inside tag brackets are ignored, and that multiple spaces outside tag brackets are rendered correctly as a single space. Test that every whitespace character is ignored. In the test details section, the whitespace and space characters are represented by their ASCII value.

Preconditions:

None, other than must be able to start BrowserMonkey to open the test data file

Test Details:

<            p                   >Some        text<    /   p    >

<p></p>

<0123456789p10111213141516>Ignore whitespace in tag brackets<171819202122232425262728293031/p>

<p>The next paragraph is the letter A alternating with a whitespace character</p>

<p>A0A1A2A3A4A5A6A7A8A9A10A11A12A13A14A15A16A</p>

<p>A17A18A19A20A21A22A23A24A25A26A27A28A29A30A31A</p>

 

Expected result:

 

Some text

 

Ignore whitespace in tag brackets

The next paragraph is the letter A alternating with a whitespace character

AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA

AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA

 

 

1.3    Starting the program

BrowserMonkey is started from the command line. A detailed description can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

 

Test Number:

ACC1-3-0001

Data file/s:

none

Description:

Test starting BrowserMonkey from the commandline with no arguments specified and neither index.html nor index.htm exist in the current directory.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must not be already open, and the current directory should not contain an index.html or index.htm file.

Test Details:

Type "java BrowserMonkey" on the command line and press enter.

 

Expected result:

Error page displayed (see Appendix A) and status bar displays the message “No page loaded”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

Test Details:

1.4    Opening an HTML document

1.4.1    Opening a document from the command line

BrowserMonkey will open documents which are held locally, or accessed via the internet. A document can be opened by specifying its path, filename and extension as an argument when starting the program from the command line. A detailed description can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

 

Test Number:

ACC1-4-0001

Data file/s:

none

Description:

Test starting BrowserMonkey from the commandline specifying a locally held filename and extension for a file which does not exist in the specified directory.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must not be already open, and the specified directory “C:\DataFiles\Manuals\” must exist and should not contain a file called “anyfile.htm”.

Test Details:

Type "java BrowserMonkey C:\DataFiles\Manuals\anyfile.html" on the command line and press enter.

 

Expected result:

Error page displayed (see Appendix A) and status bar displays the message “No page loaded”.

Covered in 2.2 Log file name

4      Requirement 4 – Tags

The browser is to render a subsection of HTML tags including:

 

  • Headings and paragraphs
  • Lists - Ordered, unordered and definition
  • Block formatting - blockquote, center and preformatted
  • Text formatting – font face and colour, italic, bold, teletype and underline
  • Horizontal rule

 

This section of the document deals with tests on conforming pages. Non-conforming page tests are described in the conformance section of the document.

7      Requirement 7 – Search

Description

BrowserMonkey will provide the ability to search the rendered text for a specified string. A detailed description can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0001

Data file/s:

none

Description:

Test search attempted when no document is open

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be opened with no document (i.e. opened from the command line with no file specified and no index.html or index.htm files present in the current directory)

Test Details:

Type "somestring" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

No action taken at all. Page and status bar remain the same as before the search button was clicked.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0002

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search button clicked but no search string input

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Ensure the search box is empty and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

No action taken at all. Page and status bar remain the same as before the search button was clicked.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0003

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test no occurrences of search string found in the open document

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "somestring" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

Status bar will display the message “No occurrences of somestring found”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0004

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search when the document is scrolled to the top of the page, at least 1 occurrence of the search string is found in the open document, and the first occurrence is visible from the top of the page.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "hello world" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

The document will remain scrolled to the top of the page.

All five occurrences of “hello world” will be highlighted with white text on a green background, e.g. hello world, and at least one of them will be visible without having to scroll down.

 

Status bar will display the message “5 occurrences of hello world found”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0005

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search when the document is scrolled to the bottom of the page, at least 1 occurrence of the search string is found in the open document, and the no occurrence is visible from the top of the page.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "hello test" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

The document will be scrolled to the top of the page.

Both occurrences of “hello test” will be highlighted with white text on a green background, e.g. hello world, and neither of them will be visible without having to scroll down.

 

Status bar will display the message “2 occurrences of hello test found”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0006

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search text case insensitivity.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "pineapple" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

The document will remain scrolled to the top of the page.

All 3 occurrences of “pineapple” will be highlighted with white text on a green background.

 

Status bar will display the message “3 occurrences of pineapple found”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

Test Number:

ACC7-0009

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search for string which is interrupted by tags, for example search for “hello” when the html file contains “he<b>llo”.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "tractor" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

The document will remain scrolled to the top of the page.

2 occurrences of “tractor” will be highlighted with white text on a green background.

 

Status bar will display the message “2 occurrences of tractor found”.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC7-0010

Data file/s:

acc7.html

Description:

Test search finds strings even when embedded in all inline and block elements.

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Type "combine" in the search box and click the search button.

 

Expected result:

The document will remain scrolled to the top of the page.

18 occurrences of “combine” will be highlighted with white text on a green background.

 

Status bar will display the message “18 occurrences of combine found”.

 

 

 

8      Requirement 8 – Zoom

BrowserMonkey will provide the ability to increase and decrease the size of the rendered text. A detailed description can be found in the corresponding section of the Requirements Specification1.

 

Test Number:

ACC8-0001

Data file/s:

none

Description:

Test zoom in attempted when no document is open

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be opened with no document (i.e. opened from the command line with no file specified and no index.html or index.htm files present in the current directory)

Test Details:

Click the zoom in button once.

 

Expected result:

No action taken at all. Page and status bar remain the same as before the zoom button was clicked.

 

 

 

Test Number:

ACC8-0002

Data file/s:

acc8.html

Description:

Test zoom in from normal to 120%

Preconditions:

BrowserMonkey must be started and the test data file opened.

Test Details:

Click the zoom in button once.

 

Expected result:

All text on page increases to approxiamtely 120% of its original size, e.g.

 

plain text

 

becomes

 

plain text
